description: This looks to me like an initial phase Sparisoma frondosum (Agassiz parrotfish or saddled parrotfish) - it has the reddish fins, pale area on top of the base of the tail, black spot at pectoral fin base, and overall mottled brown color. But this was in Martinique. Both my fish ID book (Humann & DeLoach) and online sources tell me this fish is native to Brazil and the South American coast through Venezuela, and the northern end of its range is St. Vincent, near the bottom of the lesser Antilles. I saw it on Martinique, two islands further north. Did I see it outside its range, or have I misidentified it?

Isolated colony in reef flat zone

Mother Colony at inner margin of the Reef Crest Zone (Colony #1)

This is the largest single, discrete patch or colony, which is 180-200 cm  across in the longest dimension. It probably involved fusion of several smaller, individual colonies. The top is approximately 50 cm below Mean Low Water. GPS Coordinates: 13 10.763, -059 38.414 Note the highly thickened, short branches which form a palmate structure at right where it meets the colonial zoonanthid Palythoa caribaeorum, grading into bushier forms towards the edges.

2015 Series, Colony 2 Scale is 30 cm. Estimated Maximum Linear Dimension:  46 cm To provide scale, I placed a 30 cm plastic tie over the colony, took a photograph, removed the tie and took another photo, and applied the scale to the latter accordingly. The Maximum Linear Dimension is an estimate based on this scaling, rather than a direct measurement. How old might this speciment be? Lewis et al. (1968)  recorded a mean monthly increment for branches of A. cerviocrnis in Barbados of 1.2cm or 12 cm/year (2.2 cm in Jamica).  A study in the northeastern Caribbean (Gladfelter et al., 1978) reported growth rates of  71 mm/yr for A. cervicornis, 59–82 mm/yr for A. prolifera, and 47–99 mm/yr for A. palmata, i.e similar magnitudes for the thee species. Assuming 1.2 cm per month for A. prolifera in Barbados, this colony would be approximately 2 years old (23/1.2). The largest, specimen clearly derived from one individual propagule was 52 cm MLD, so not much older. The smallest was only 13 cm, so perhaps it is less than 6 months old. The 3 largest  colonies (specimens 1,5, 16 with MLDs of 190, 100, 62 cm appear to have involved fusion of 2 or more  separate colonies, so might be up to 5 years old, possibly younger. The largest colony was likely the founder colony,  others developing by asexual fragmentation from that colony or one of its early offspring. Lewis, J.B. et al. 1968. Comparative Growth Rates of Some Reef Corals in the Caribbean. Available at https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a080111.pdf Gladfelter, E.H. et al. 1978. Growth Rates of Five Reef-Building Corals in the Northeastern Caribbean. Bulletin of Marine Science,  28:. 728-734.

Genus: Sargassum

They are generally brown or dark green in color and consist of a holdfast, a stipe, and a frond. Oogonia and antheridia occur in conceptacles embedded in receptacles on special branches.[6] Some species have berrylike gas-filled bladders that help the fronds float to promote photosynthesis. Many have a rough, sticky texture that, along with a robust but flexible body, helps it withstand strong water currents.

description: The fish was about 8 and a half inches long and 5 inches tall. The main body of the fish was shaped in an egg shape. The fish’s mainbody color was a very light green than almost turned white at the bottom. The fish had a small yellow pectoral fin bellow the middle of his mainbody on both sides of his body. The fish had one black eye near the front of his body which was also on each side of his body as well. On the end of his mainbody there was a long curved bright yellow caudal fin that was shaped like a whale’s tail fin. At the bottom end of the fish’s mainbody was another fin called the anal fin and was also bright yellow. On the same spot on the top there was a bright yellow dorsal fin. At the bottom middle of the fish’s main body there was another bright yellow fin called the pelvic fin. There were 2 black stripes that went down the side of the fish’s face. There were some bright yellow lines that went across the fish’s body. When I was scuba diving I saw a yellow and black blur in my peripheral vision. When I looked to see what the blur was it had hidden behind a rock. So then when I looked behind the rock I saw the fish swimming around coral. It seemed like he was trying to figure out what the coral on the side of the rock he was hiding behind was.
place_guess: North Atlantic Ocean, Nassau, Bahamas, BS

description: The small fish was only about 8 inches long and 6 inches tall at its tallest point. Its mainbody was dark blue/turquoise and shaped like an egg. Its caudal fin was also dark blue/torquoise in the middle but had a thick outer line of light blue that made me think of electricity. The caudal fin looked like a crab claw because it caved in at the end. The fish’s lips were also the same electric blue of the caudal fin outline. The fish’s dorsal fin was also electric blue as well as the fish’s anal fin, pelvic fin and the fish’s pectoral fins. The fish’s eyes were located at the top near the front of his face and there was one on each side. When I first spotted the fish I was far away and thought it was some weird type of coral because it seemed to be growing out of the rock and I couldn’t tell they were moving. As I got closer I could see that they weren’t coral at all but, a school of blue fish hovering next to a rock. At the time I took this photo they weren’t doing much. A couple of them kept swimming under the rock and going through its tunnels while a few of them were just hovering around each other.
place_guess: North Atlantic Ocean, Nassau, Bahamas, BS

description: When I was scuba diving (I am patty certified) I saw these pork fish looking for food (little crustaceans and mollusks). When I got closer the fish started swimming away from me. This fish obviously like to swim in schools. These pork fish with their yellow tails and fins. This pork fish had two black lines both streaking from top to bottom but one almost touched the fin while the other coats the fishes eye. This was on both sides of the fish’s face. The fishes body was streaked with gold and blue stripes. The fish was about as long as the length from my ankle to my knee, so about 15.5 inches long.

When I was scuba diving (I am patty certified) I saw this fish swimming away from a bigger fish. This fish’s body was a teal color with a natural green color strip in the middle from the green tail to the fish’s eye. the fish’s fins were also green. This fish was about a foot and a half long.

When I was scuba diving (I am patty certified) I saw this shy fish that was looking for food, very hesitantly looking in crevices and wholes, until he saw me. This blue eyed fish was very fast and scarred so I had to zoom in on the camera. This fish with his shamrock and forest green striped body, topped off with two blue suspecting eyes. This fish was about a foot long.
